	<ext_description linkend="Information_rights_arm.Applied_information_usage_right.right_applied">
the right which is applied to the items
</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Information_rights_arm  Entity: Information_right  
   <express_ref linkend="information_rights:arm:Information_rights_arm.Information_right"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Information_rights_arm.Information_right">
An <b>Information_right</b> is a definition what may or may not be done with an item of information in the sense of legal
rights and obligations.
<example number="1">Copyright is an <b>Information_right</b>.</example>
		<example number="2">For the purposes of developing a new system, details of government furnished equipment may be made available to a particular project
team. The team may copy and use the information internally, but may not pass it on, either to a third part, or to another team, and must
destroy the information at the end of the contract.</example>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Information_rights_arm  Entity: Information_right  Attribute: id 
   <express_ref linkend="information_rights:arm:Information_rights_arm.Information_right.id"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Information_rights_arm.Information_right.id">
an identifier for the right.
<note> The identifier should be unique, however there is no meaningful way of specifying the scope over which it
is unique.</note>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Information_rights_arm  Entity: Information_right  Attribute: name 
   <express_ref linkend="information_rights:arm:Information_rights_arm.Information_right.name"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Information_rights_arm.Information_right.name">
the word or words by which the right is known.
</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Information_rights_arm  Entity: Information_right  Attribute: description 
   <express_ref linkend="information_rights:arm:Information_rights_arm.Information_right.description"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Information_rights_arm.Information_right.description">
the text that provides further information about what the right allows the user to do, and what is not
permitted.
The value of this attribute need not be specified.
</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Information_rights_arm  Entity: Information_right  Attribute: restriction 
   <express_ref linkend="information_rights:arm:Information_rights_arm.Information_right.restriction"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Information_rights_arm.Information_right.restriction">
the description of any conditions and limitations that apply to the
exercise of the right.
The value of this attribute need not be specified.
<example number="3"> The <b>description</b> of the right states that copying is permitted within the project
team only, whereas the <b>restriction</b> notes the additional constraint that the information must be destroyed
at the end of the project. </example>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Information_rights_arm  Entity: Information_usage_right  
   <express_ref linkend="information_rights:arm:Information_rights_arm.Information_usage_right"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Information_rights_arm.Information_usage_right">
An <b>Information_usage_right</b> is an application an <express_ref linkend="information_rights:arm:Information_rights_arm.Information_right"/> to a particular usage context.
<note number="1">One view of the distinction between an <express_ref linkend="information_rights:arm:Information_rights_arm.Information_right"/> and an <b>Information_usage_right</b>
is that the <express_ref linkend="information_rights:arm:Information_rights_arm.Information_right"/> represents a standard clause in a contract, whereas an <b>Information_usage_right</b>
represents the fact that the clause is used in a particular contract. </note>
		<note number="2">The context for the usage can be defined through the contract which defines the right,
the organization that grants the right, the person or organization which is granted the right, and any dates such as the starting
or ending dates for the right. The meaning of each association is identified through the roles of the assignments, and these are defined
through reference data. </note>
		<note number="3">The <express_ref linkend="approval:arm:Approval_arm.Approval"/> of an <b>Information_usage_right</b> carries the meaning that the right
is granted to all information items in the relevant context, as opposed to the approval of an <express_ref linkend="information_rights:arm:Information_rights_arm.Applied_information_usage_right"/>
which is limited to particular items.</note>
		<note number="4">
			<b>Information_usage_right</b> provides a mechanism for recording significant rights within
a product database. The legal significance of the presence or absence of a right is outside the scope
of this part of ISO 10303</note>
	</ext_description>
